# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dspm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:dspm/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Data governance involves delegating authority over data and exercising that authority through decision-making processes.
[src:dspm/data-governance] It plays a role in enhancing the value of data assets.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Data governance at the macro level involves regulating cross-border data flows among countries, which is more precisely termed *international data governance*.
[src:dspm/data-governance] There have been several international groups established by research organizations that aim to grant access to their data.
[src:dspm/data-governance] These groups that enable an exchange of data are, as a result, exposed to domestic and international legal interpretations that ultimately decide how data is used.
[src:dspm/data-governance] However, as of 2023, there are no international laws or agreements specifically focused on data protection.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Data governance is the set of principles, policies, and processes that guide the effective and responsible use of data within an organization.
[src:dspm/data-governance] It creates a framework for decision making, accountability, and oversight across the data lifecycle, from creation and storage to sharing and disposal.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Data governance is closely linked with data management, which provides the practical methods to carry out governance objectives.
[src:dspm/data-governance] These methods include data quality assurance, metadata management, master data management, security controls, and compliance monitoring.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Together, governance and management aim to maximize the value of data as a strategic asset, reduce risks from misuse or inaccuracy, and ensure compliance with regulatory, ethical, and business requirements.
[src:dspm/data-governance] The importance of this discipline has grown with the rise of big data, cloud computing, and artificial intelligence, where consistent standards and stewardship are essential for privacy protection, interoperability, and informed decision making.
[src:dspm/data-governance] In 2010, they published a data governance framework based on five components: data principles (which define the data's purpose by an organization), data quality, metadata, data access, and data lifecycle.
[src:dspm/data-governance] In 2017, the ISO released a framework for data governance, ISO/IEC 38505-1:2017.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Due to the increased use of large language models and the datasets used to train them, a 2022 paper proposed a data governance framework in the context of human rights.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Other well-known data governance frameworks include ISO 8000, the CMMI Data Management Maturity (DMM) Model, and DAMA-DMBOK.
[src:dspm/data-governance] While data governance initiatives can be driven by a desire to improve data quality, they are often driven by C-level leaders responding to external regulations.
[src:dspm/data-governance] In a recent report conducted by the CIO WaterCooler community, 54% stated the key driver was efficiencies in processes; 39% - regulatory requirements; and only 7% customer service.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Examples of these regulations include Sarbanes–Oxley Act, Basel I, Basel II, HIPAA, GDPR, cGMP, and a number of data privacy regulations.
[src:dspm/data-governance] To achieve compliance with these regulations, business processes and controls require formal management processes to govern the data subject to these regulations.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Successful programs identify drivers that are meaningful to both supervisory and executive leadership.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Common themes among the external regulations center on the need to manage risk.
[src:dspm/data-governance] The risks can be financial misstatement, inadvertent release of sensitive data, or poor data quality for key decisions.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Methods to manage these risks vary from industry to industry.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Examples of commonly referenced best practices and guidelines include COBIT, ISO/IEC 38500, and others.
[src:dspm/data-governance] The proliferation of regulations and standards creates challenges for data governance professionals, particularly when multiple regulations overlap the data being managed.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Organizations often launch data governance initiatives to address these challenges.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Data governance initiatives improve the quality of data by assigning a team responsible for data's accuracy, completeness, consistency, timeliness, validity, and uniqueness.
[src:dspm/data-governance] This team usually consists of executive leadership, project management, line-of-business managers, and data stewards.
[src:dspm/data-governance] The team usually employs a methodology for tracking and improving enterprise data, such as Six Sigma, and tools for data mapping, profiling, cleansing, and monitoring data.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Many data governance initiatives are also inspired by past attempts to fix information quality at the departmental level, which can lead to incongruent and redundant data quality processes.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Most large companies have many applications and databases that can not easily share information.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Therefore, knowledge workers within large organizations may not have access to the data they need to best do their jobs.
[src:dspm/data-governance] When they do have access to the data, the data quality may be poor.
[src:dspm/data-governance] By setting up a data governance practice or corporate data authority (individual or area responsible for determining how to proceed, in the best interest of the business, when a data issue arises), these problems can be mitigated.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Implementation of a data governance initiative may vary in scope as well as origin.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Sometimes, an executive mandate will arise to initiate an enterprise-wide effort.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Sometimes the mandate will be to create a pilot project or projects, limited in scope and objectives, aimed at either resolving existing issues or demonstrating value.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Sometimes, an initiative originates from lower down in the organization's hierarchy and will be deployed in a limited scope to demonstrate value to potential sponsors higher up in the organization.
[src:dspm/data-governance] The initial scope of an implementation can vary greatly as well, from review of a one-off IT system to a cross-organization initiative.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Leaders of successful data governance programs declared at the Data Governance Conference in Orlando, FL, in December 2006, that data governance is about 80 to 95 percent communication.
[src:dspm/data-governance] That stated, it is a given that many of the objectives of a data governance program must be accomplished with appropriate tools.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Many vendors are now positioning their products as data governance tools.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Due to the different focus areas of various data governance initiatives, a given tool may or may not be appropriate.
[src:dspm/data-governance] Additionally, many tools that are not marketed as governance tools address governance needs and demands.
[src:dspm/data-security] Proper data security practices reduce the risk of data breaches, including unauthorized access, theft and loss of individual data such as identity documents and bank data.
[src:dspm/data-security] Data security is part of information security.
[src:dspm/data-security] Disk encryption refers to encryption technology that encrypts data on a hard disk drive.
[src:dspm/data-security] It takes data from a storage device and coverts it into an unreadable format.
[src:dspm/data-security] Disk encryption typically takes form in either software (see disk encryption software) or hardware (see disk encryption hardware) which can be used together.
[src:dspm/data-security] Disk encryption is often referred to as on-the-fly encryption (OTFE) or transparent encryption.
[src:dspm/data-security] Full disk encryption encrypts each individual sector of a disk volume.
[src:dspm/data-security] Files and user data are encrypted to hinder unauthorized users from accessing without a decryption key.
[src:dspm/data-security] A diversifier permits a plaintext of a specific disk sector to be encrypted into different ciphertexts, which does not require additional storage, such as an initialization vector (IV) or message authentication code (MAC).
[src:dspm/data-security] Software-based security solutions encrypt the data to protect it from theft.
[src:dspm/data-security] However, a malicious program or a hacker could corrupt the data to make it unrecoverable, making the system unusable.
[src:dspm/data-security] Hardware-based security solutions prevent read and write access to data, which provides very strong protection against tampering and unauthorized access.
[src:dspm/data-security] Hardware-based security or assisted computer security offers an alternative to software-only computer security.
[src:dspm/data-security] Security tokens such as those using PKCS#11 or a mobile phone may be more secure due to the physical access required in order to be compromised.
[src:dspm/data-security] Access is enabled only when the token is connected and the correct PIN is entered (see two-factor authentication).
[src:dspm/data-security] However, dongles can be used by anyone who can gain physical access to it.
[src:dspm/data-security] Newer technologies in hardware-based security solve this problem by offering full proof of security for data.
[src:dspm/data-security] Working off hardware-based security: A hardware device allows a user to log in, log out and set different levels through manual actions.
[src:dspm/data-security] Many devices use biometric technology to prevent malicious users from logging in, logging out, and changing privilege levels.
[src:dspm/data-security] The current state of a user of the device is read by controllers in peripheral devices such as hard disks.
[src:dspm/data-security] Illegal access by a malicious user or a malicious program is interrupted based on the current state of a user by hard disk and DVD controllers making illegal access to data impossible.
[src:dspm/data-security] Hardware-based access control is more secure than the protection provided by the operating systems as operating systems are vulnerable to malicious attacks by viruses and hackers.
[src:dspm/data-security] The data on hard disks can be corrupted after malicious access is obtained.
[src:dspm/data-security] With hardware-based protection, the software cannot manipulate the user privilege levels.
[src:dspm/data-security] A hacker or a malicious program cannot gain access to secure data protected by hardware or perform unauthorized privileged operations.
[src:dspm/data-security] This assumption is broken only if the hardware itself is malicious or contains a backdoor.
[src:dspm/data-security] The hardware protects the operating system image and file system privileges from being tampered with.
[src:dspm/data-security] Therefore, a completely secure system can be created using a combination of hardware-based security and secure system administration policies.
[src:dspm/data-security] Backup is the process of reproducing copies of essential data and storing in a separate, secured place.
[src:dspm/data-security] It is used to ensure data that is lost can be recovered from another source.
[src:dspm/data-security] Backups contains a minimum of one copy of the data that requires preservation.
[src:dspm/data-security] It is considered essential to keep a backup of any data in most industries and the process is recommended for any files of importance to a user.
[src:dspm/data-security] There are 3 types of backups; full backups, incremental backups, and differential backups.
[src:dspm/data-security] Full backups secure all data from a production system, such as a server, database, or other connected data source.
[src:dspm/data-security] It is impossible to lose all data in a full backup if a breach or corruption were to occur.
[src:dspm/data-security] Full backups require a significantly large amount of time to back up and may be time-consuming taking hours to days to complete.
[src:dspm/data-security] Incremental backups only secures changed data since last backup.
[src:dspm/data-security] While all backups are done in full backups, incremental backups only save data that is recently or frequently changed.
[src:dspm/data-security] Incremental backups require lower storage costs making it a prominent solution for growing datasets.
[src:dspm/data-security] Data privacy (or information privacy) is the right for individual's data to be secured to obstruct the use of unauthorized access.
[src:dspm/data-security] It gives individuals control over their data and how it can be shared to third parties.
[src:dspm/data-security] The U.S Privacy Protection Law (see Privacy laws of the United States) requires organizations to inform individuals of how their data is collected and when a data breach occurs.
[src:dspm/data-security] By implementing an encryption, it ensures that private data is unreadable to cybercriminals.
[src:dspm/data-security] Data masking of structured data is the process of obscuring (masking) specific data within a database table or cell to ensure that data security is maintained and sensitive information is not exposed to unauthorized personnel.
[src:dspm/data-security] Data masking is a form of encryption, as it obscures data by modifying particular letters and numbers to keep data concealed and protected from potential hackers.
[src:dspm/data-security] The individual that has access to the code that decrypts the replaced characters are the only ones that can uncover the data.
[src:dspm/data-security] Data erasure (or data deletion, data destruction) is a method of software-based overwriting that permanently clears all electronic data residing on a hard drive or other digital media to ensure that no sensitive data is lost when an asset is retired or reused.
[src:dspm/data-security] Article 17: Right to be Forgotten states that users have the right to permanently remove all of their private information from their old devices/services to give people more control over their data.
[src:dspm/data-security] Users are able to switch between devices efficiently.
[src:dspm/data-security] Malware (or malicious software) is designed to destroy, corrupt or gain unauthorized access to a computer for the purpose of stealing, or destroying data.
[src:dspm/data-security] Hackers who use malware typically utilize many types of malware, which includes computer virus, computer worms, ransomware, spyware and Trojan horse to create a vast system of disruption and cause easy data theft.
[src:dspm/data-security] One of the victims of the vast system of disruption includes healthcare workers, who are targeted by compromised systems by infections and then having their data attacked.
[src:dspm/data-security] Attackers are able to create websites that are very similar to original websites, which makes it difficult to detect a fake website, causing individuals to fall for giving in information.
[src:dspm/data-security] Phishing attackers use human emotion to exploit them, such as making them feel fear, urgency, sympathy with the message being sent by the sender.
[src:dspm/data-security] Emails (Or Email spoofing) with impersonated companies and fake websites copying the original are ways to exploit people.
[src:dspm/data-security] Email spoofing show false names and emails of the original ones to copy several banks, companies and agencies, using warnings to manipulate people into feeling urgent about the email.
[src:dspm/data-security] In the UK, the Data Protection Act is used to ensure that personal data is accessible to those whom it concerns, and provides redress to individuals if there are inaccuracies.
[src:dspm/data-security] This is particularly important to ensure individuals are treated fairly, for example for credit checking purposes.
[src:dspm/data-security] The Data Protection Act states that only individuals and companies with legitimate and lawful reasons can process personal information and cannot be shared.
[src:dspm/data-security] Data Privacy Day is an international holiday started by the Council of Europe that occurs every January 28.
[src:dspm/data-security] Since the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) of the European Union (EU) became law on May 25, 2018, organizations may face significant penalties of up to €20 million or 4% of their annual revenue if they do not comply with the regulation.
[src:dspm/data-security] It is intended that GDPR will force organizations to understand their data privacy risks and take the appropriate measures to reduce the risk of unauthorized disclosure of consumers’ private information.
[src:dspm/data-security] The Trusted Computing Group is an organization that helps standardize computing security technologies.
[src:dspm/data-security] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) is a proprietary international information security standard for organizations that handle cardholder information for the major debit, credit, prepaid, e-purse, automated teller machines, and point of sale cards.
[src:dspm/data-security] The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) proposed by the European Commission will strengthen and unify data protection for individuals within the EU, whilst addressing the export of personal data outside the EU.
[src:dspm/data-security] The four types of technical safeguards are access controls, flow controls, inference controls, and data encryption.
[src:dspm/data-security] Access controls manage user entry and data manipulation, while flow controls regulate data dissemination.
[src:dspm/data-security] Inference controls prevent deduction of confidential information from statistical databases and data encryption prevents unauthorized access to confidential information.
[src:dspm/data-security] Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) is a law that requires entities such as healthcare providers to keep patient confidentiality for three required safeguards: administrative, physical, and technical.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] This refers to information that is already a matter of public record or knowledge.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] With regard to government and private organizations, access to or release of such information may be requested by any member of the public, and there are often formal processes laid out for how to do so.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The accessibility of government-held public records is an important part of government transparency, accountability to its citizens, and the values of democracy.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Public records may furthermore refer to information about identifiable individuals that is not considered confidential, including but not limited to: census records, criminal records, sex offender registry files, and voter registration.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] This includes business information that is not subjected to special protection and may be routinely shared with anyone inside or outside of the business.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] However, there are situations in which the release of personal information could have a negative effect on its owner.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] For example, a person trying to avoid a stalker will be inclined to further restrict access to such personal information.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Furthermore, a person's SSN or SIN, credit card numbers, and other financial information may be considered private if their disclosure might lead to crimes such as identity theft or fraud.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Some types of private information, including records of a person's health care, education, and employment may be protected by privacy laws.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Unauthorized disclosure of private information can make the perpetrator liable for civil remedies and may in some cases be subject to criminal penalties.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Even though they are often used interchangeably, personal information is sometimes distinguished from private information, or personally identifiable information.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The latter is distinct from the former in that Private information can be used to identify a unique individual.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Personal information, on the other hand, is information belonging to the private life of an individual that cannot be used to uniquely identify that individual.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] This can range from an individual's favourite colour, to the details of their domestic life.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The latter is a common example of personal information that is also regarded as sensitive, where the individual sharing these details with a trusted listener would prefer for it not to be shared with anyone else, and the sharing of which may result in unwanted consequences.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Confidential business information (CBI) refers to information whose disclosure may harm the business.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Such information may include trade secrets, sales and marketing plans, new product plans, notes associated with patentable inventions, customer and supplier information, financial data, and more.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Under TSCA, CBI is defined as proprietary information, considered confidential to the submitter, the release of which would cause substantial business injury to the owner.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The US EPA may as of 2016, review and determine if a company´s claim is valid.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Classified information generally refers to information that is subject to special security classification regulations imposed by many national governments, the disclosure of which may cause harm to national interests and security.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The protocol of restriction imposed upon such information is categorized into a hierarchy of classification levels in almost every national government worldwide, with the most restricted levels containing information that may cause the greatest danger to national security if leaked.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Authorized access is granted to individuals on a need to know basis who have also passed the appropriate level of security clearance.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Classified information can be reclassified to a different level or declassified (made available to the public) depending on changes of situation or new intelligence.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Classified information may also be further denoted with the method of communication or access.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] For example, Protectively Marked "Secret" Eyes Only or Protectively Marked "Secret" Encrypted transfer only.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Indicating that the document must be physically read by the recipient and cannot be openly discussed for example over a telephone conversation or that the communication can be sent only using encrypted means.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Often mistakenly listed as meaning for the eyes of the intended recipient only the anomaly becomes apparent when the additional tag "Not within windowed area" is also used.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Data privacy concerns exist in various aspects of daily life wherever personal data is stored and collected, such as on the internet, in medical records, financial records, and expression of political opinions.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] In over 80 countries in the world, personally identifiable information is protected by information privacy laws, which outline limits to the collection and use of personally identifiable information by public and private entities.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Such laws usually require entities to give clear and unambiguous notice to the individual of the types of data being collected, its reason for collection, and planned uses of the data.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] In consent-based legal frameworks, explicit consent of the individual is required as well.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The European Union passed the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), replacing the earlier Data Protection Directive.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The regulation was adopted on 27 April 2016.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] It became enforceable from 25 May 2018 after a two-year transition period and, unlike a directive, it does not require national governments to pass any enabling legislation, and is thus directly binding and applicable.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] "The proposed new EU data protection regime extends the scope of the EU data protection law to all foreign companies processing data of EU residents.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] In Canada, the Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA) regulates the collection and use of personal data and electronic documents by public and private organizations.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] PIPEDA is in effect in all federal and provincial jurisdictions, except provinces where existing privacy laws are determined to be “substantially similar”.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Whether being regulated or self regulated, the laws require to establish ways at which access to sensitive information is limited to the people with different roles, thus in essence requiring establishment of the "sensitive data domain" model and mechanisms of its protection.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Some of the domains have a guideline in form of pre-defined models such as "Safe Harbor" of HIPAA, based on the research of Latanya Sweeny and established privacy industry metrics.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Additionally, many other countries have enacted their own legislature regarding data privacy protection, and more are still in the process of doing so.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The confidentiality of sensitive business information is established through non-disclosure agreements, a legally binding contract between two parties in a professional relationship.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] NDAs may be one-way, such as in the case of an employee receiving confidential information about the employing organization, or two-way between businesses needing to share information with one another to accomplish a business goal.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Depending on the severity of consequences, a violation of non-disclosure may result in employment loss, loss of business and client contacts, criminal charges or a civil lawsuit, and a hefty sum in damages.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Unlike personal and private information, there is no internationally recognized framework protecting trade secrets, or even an agreed-upon definition of the term “trade secret”.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] However, many countries and political jurisdictions have taken the initiative to account for the violation of commercial confidentiality in their criminal or civil laws.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] For example, under the US Economic Espionage Act of 1996, it is a federal crime in the United States to misappropriate trade secrets with the knowledge that it will benefit a foreign power, or will injure the owner of the trade secret.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] More commonly, breach of commercial confidentiality falls under civil law, such as in the United Kingdom.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] In some developing countries, trade secret laws are either non-existent or poorly developed and offer little substantial protection.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] In many countries, unauthorized disclosure of classified information is a criminal offence, and may be punishable by fines, prison sentence, or even the death penalty, depending on the severity of the violation.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] For less severe violations, civil sanctions may be imposed, ranging from reprimand to revoking of security clearance and subsequent termination of employment.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Whistleblowing is the intentional disclosure of sensitive information to a third-party with the intention of revealing alleged illegal, immoral, or otherwise harmful actions.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] There are many examples of present and former government employees disclosing classified information regarding national government misconduct to the public and media, in spite of the criminal consequences that await them.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Espionage, or spying, involves obtaining sensitive information without the permission or knowledge of its holder.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The use of spies is a part of national intelligence gathering in most countries, and has been used as a political strategy by nation-states since ancient times.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] It is unspoken knowledge in international politics that countries are spying on one another all the time, even their allies.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Computer security is information security applied to computing and network technology, and is a significant and ever-growing field in computer science.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The term computer insecurity, on the other hand, is the concept that computer systems are inherently vulnerable to attack, and therefore an evolving arms race between those who exploit existing vulnerabilities in security systems and those who must then engineer new mechanisms of security.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] A number of security concerns have arisen in the recent years as increasing amounts of sensitive information at every level have found their primary existence in digital form.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] At the personal level, credit card fraud, internet fraud, and other forms of identity theft have become widespread concerns that individuals need to be aware of on a day-to-day basis.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The existence of large databases of classified information on computer networks is also changing the face of domestic and international politics.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Cyber-warfare and cyber espionage is becoming of increasing importance to the national security and strategy of nations around the world, and it is estimated that 120 nations around the world are currently actively engaged in developing and deploying technology for these purposes.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] Philosophies and internet cultures such as open-source governance, hacktivism, and the popular hacktivist slogan "information wants to be free" reflects some of the cultural shifts in perception towards political and government secrecy.
[src:dspm/information-sensitivity] The popular, controversial WikiLeaks is just one of many manifestations of a growing cultural sentiment that is becoming an additional challenge to the security and integrity of classified information.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:dspm/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
